jje@aib.com (Jeremy J. Epstein) writes:

>lharnisch@delphi.com wrote:
>: Speaking of which....
>:I recently read an article in the Washington Post (I believe) about NSA museum
>:that had a variety of Engima machines on display hat one could examine,
>:meddle with etc.
>: 	Has anyone visited yet and if so, what's it like?

>I summarized the Post article in a recent article in RISKS (aka comp.risks).
>I visited the museum a couple of weeks ago; it's got a few neat things,
>but it lacks a lot of depth.  For example, there's no explanation of how
>any of the cryptographic devices work; they just show them.  It's worth
>stopping in for an hour if you're in the neighborhood, but I wouldn't
>go out of my way for it.

>To get there from Washington DC, take the Baltimore-Washington Parkway
>(MD 295) north.  Exit at Route 32 east.  Large brown signs will direct
>you to make an immediate left, and then follow the gravel road around
>behind a Shell station to a barbed-wire surrounded building.

For the rest of us who cannot easily travel to Washington or
England, are there any good books with pictures of these museums?
Are there any museum pamphlets?

